@@dASSASSIN@@W

@@dHistory@@W
  No guild claims the founding of the Assassin tradition -- that is by
  design. The earliest known practitioners were royal intelligence agents
  in a long-dissolved empire, trained to remove obstacles without the
  political cost of open warfare. Their methods passed from handler to
  operative in a chain of careful instruction, each generation learning that
  patience and positioning mattered more than strength. When the empire fell,
  its agents scattered and sold their expertise piecemeal. Most lineages
  degraded into common cutthroats; those who kept the original philosophy
  intact produced something rarer: practitioners who understood that the
  perfect kill requires as much study as any academic discipline.

Assassins are patient executioners. They win by controlling first contact,
creating one lethal opening, and ending the fight before opponents can answer.

